msDesc.head: Dioscorides, De uirtutibus herbarum and other medical texts

supportDesc.support: Modern parchment endleaves, all medieval leaves are parchment.

extent.seg: 3 modern parchment endleaves + 1 stub + 1 leaf | 5 (4 leaves + a singleton) | 4 | 7 ; 132 (plus 2 post-medieval paper slip and stub) ; 13 + 3 leaves.
extent.note: The three leaves at the front (ff. [a]-[c])and the back (ff. [d]-[f]) of the manuscript are modern parchment endleaves and have not been digitised (2023).

foliation.note: Foliated in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals in the upper outer corner of each recto. Three leaves were omitted from this sequence: a post-medieval slip of paper fixed to the upper margin of f. 45v with an adhesive, a post-medieval stub of paper between ff. 60 and 61, and the leaf between the leaves designated f. 93v and f. 94r. These omitted leaves have been assigned the folio designations [45a] [60a] and [93a] respectively, in order to produce a functional TEI-XML catalogue record. Some endleaves were also not included in this sequence and so were assigned folio numbers in order to produce a functional TEI-XML catalogue record; these designations are enclosed in [square brackets].

binding.p: Medieval binding, perhaps 13th century with extensive late-20th and early-21st century repairs. Fully bound in undecorated tawed skin over wood boards. Original tawed skin covers lifted, a replacement tawed skin cover added over the boards and back, and the original tawed skin covers replaced over the faces of the boards. Two raised bands on the spine. Replacement head and tail bands visible and sewn in a neutral cream yarn through the cover material over the back. Remnants of a strap-and-pin fastening visible as a slit for the strap end in the centre of the fore edge of the left board and a puncture mark in the centre of the cover material on the right board, and aligned puncture marks with metal-oxide staining on the medieval parchment endleaves at the end of the volume (e.g., f. 160v).

Original parchment pastedowns and guard strips lifted, these are now ff. [i]-[ii] and f. 160. Replacement parchment pastedowns and endleaves ff. [a]-[c] and [d]-[f] added in the late 20th or early 21st century.
All quires taken down and remounted during late 20th or early 21st century conservation work, small paper guardstrips visible between most quires and some (?all) quires resewn.
Housed in a dark green box with a label bearing the shelfmark 'MS QD 2' in gold.
Cover dimensions (L x W x D): 215 x 155 x 60 mm

provenance.p: Owned by a Master Herbert the Doctor Master Herbert the Doctor , who gave this book and supposedly six others to the community of Durham Cathedral Priory: the donation is recorded in this manuscript on f. 2r in a ?mid 13th century hand. A record of this donation 'Hii sunt libri magister herbertus medicus dedit sancto cuthberto' is preserved in a mid-12th century hand in Durham, Cathedral Library, MS B.IV.24 ('The Durham Cantor's Book'), f. 2r , which records the donation of seven multi-text medical manuscripts by Master Herbert. The entry for Jesus MS Q.D.2 in the donation list preserved in the Durham Cantor's Book is as follows: 'Exceptiones de libro pauli . Priscianus de accentibus . Parabolae Petri amphulsi . Liber Aurelii Ambrosii . Liber Diascoridis . Liber de natura lapidum . in uno uolumine'.

provenance.p: Owned by the Durham Cathedral Priory community following the donation of the volume in probably the third quarter of the 12th century by Master Herbert the Doctor Master Herbert the Doctor . Undated records of the donation can be found in Durham, Cathedral Library, MS B.IV.24 ('The Durham Cantor's Book'), f. 2r and Jesus College MS Q.D.2 itself on f. 2r.

Owned by Thomas Man Thomas Man (b. c. 1655, d. 1690), who was admitted to Jesus College as a pensioner in 1671, took his B.A., M.A., and M.D., there, was a Fellow of that College from 1676 until his death in 1690.

msItem.title: Extracts from the Saturnalia
msItem.author: Macrobius
msItem.incipit: 6r Animo melius distincta seruantur . Oportet seruari in conuiuio sermones
msItem.explicit: 8v pitagore praecepta audiret . Secundo et octogesimo etatis sue anno decesu . Sit .
msItem.note:
Divided into four parts with the following incipits:
1. Animo melius distincta seruantur
2. Cum quidam stolidus audiente socrate diceret
3. Apius claudius crebro solebat dicere
4. Cato octogesimum sextum agens annum

Attributed to Petrus Alfonsi Petrus Alfonsi in the late 12th/early 13th century list of the contents of this volume on f. 2r ('dicta quedam petri alfunsi'), but the text itself in this Part is untitled. This text has also been identified as the Parabolae of Petrus Alfonsi by E. Kealey, but J. V. Tolan rejected this identification and classifies it as extracts from the Saturnalia by Macrobius. Tolan also identified another manuscript which contains the same incipit, Vatican City, Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana, MS Reg.lat.1575, ff. 93r-94v, but was unable to compare the manuscripts directly. As BAV Reg.lat.1575 has been digitisied, it has been possible to compare the two manuscripts, and BAV Reg.lat.1575 contains the first of the four sections (ff. 6r-7r 'Animo melius distincta ... loquacitatis agitantur') of this text.

msItem.title: The Alphabetical Latin Dioscorides ('De uirtutibus herbarum')
msItem.author: Dioscorides
msItem.textLang: Latin with occasional glosses in Middle English
msItem.incipit: 17r Multi uoluerunt auctores antiqui de de uirtutibus herbarum et compositione oleorum scribere
18r Acorus id est herba ueneria . uel afrodisia . uel piper apium
msItem.explicit: 145r Zedoaria calide uirtutis est et uiscide . unde et lumbricos occidit . ructum facit . et stomacho aptum est . cuius dolorem antiquum ieiunis sumptum masticatione tollit
msItem.note: The text in this manuscript is the alphabetical recension of the herbal of Dioscorides, usually described in Anglophone scholarship as the 'Alphabetical Latin Dioscorides' to distinguish it from the older non-alphabetised recensions. The oldest survivng copy of the Alphabetical Latin Dioscorides is dated to the 11th century, is incomplete, and is now Leiden, Bibliotheek der Universiteit, MS Voss. lat. 4Â° 1 ('VLQ 1'), ff. 1r-32v. Jesus College MS Q.D.2 is the second or third oldest surviving copy alongside the one in Bologna, Biblioteca Universitaria, 620 (lat. 378), ff. 22r-104v, which is also dated to the 12th century. See Riddle, 'Dioscorides', esp pp. 23-27 for further information.

signatures.p: Occasional leaf signatures added inconsistently in this Part. The first four rectos of Quire 12 are marked with a nesting 'v' shape in their lower margin according to their position in the quire, e.g., f. 76r is the third leaf in that quire and it has 3 'v's in its lower margin. The first four rectos of Quire 15 are marked with tally marks in their lower outer corner according to their position in the quire.

There are several sets of medieval quire signatures in this Part - all appear to be roughly contemporary with the production of the volume and so each will be described in turn and then the relationship(s) between them will be discussed.

The first set of quire signatures in this Part uses large Roman numerals set in the centre of the lower margin on the first recto of each quire (see e.g., the 'VII' on f. 25r for an untrimmed example); this sequence runs from 'VI' on the present Quire 4, to 'XXII' on the present Quire 20, and several of these signatures have been fully or partially trimmed away. There is a possible remnant of a XXIV signature at the bottom of f. 156r at the start of the present Quire 22, but it is not possible to be completely certain due to trimming.

The second set of quire signatures is written in Roman numerals in light brown ink in the centre of the lower margin of the last verso of most quires in this Part. This sequence has been mostly trimmed away and is not complete, the remaining signatures are a 'i' at the end of the present Quire 4 (f. 24v), the present Quires 10-15 signed 'viii' to 'xiii' and the present Quire 17 signed 'xv'. If the sequence continued uninterrupted from the 'i' on the present Quire 4 then the present Quire 10 should be 'vii' and not 'viii', but there is no obvious loss of a whole quire of text anywhere between the present Quires 4 and 10.

The third set of quire signatures is alphabetical and is found in the lower margin of the first recto of some quires in this Part. Examples of the third sequence are as follows: on the first leaf of the present Quire 8 (f. 47r, the signature 'c. ii'; 'c. xxv' on the first leaf of the present Quire 9; 'cin et ed' on the first leaf of the present Quire 10 and the recipes in that quire run from 'cincus' to 'ediosmum'; 'F .i. I .ii.' on the first leaf of the present Quire 12 and the recipes in that quire run from 'fel' to 'Iacinctus'; '... et o i in lacÃ¾ l' on the first leaf of the present Quire 13 and the recipes in that quire run from 'ius' to 'litargirum'. There are traces of this sequence on the first recto of several other quires, but most of the details have been lost to trimming.

note.p: Marginal additions to the Dioscorides text in hands from the 12th-17th centuries, typically glossing plant names or adding further recipes or comments.

Post-medieval paper slip, f. [45a] fixed along its upper edge to the upper margin of f. 45v with an adhesive. The slip bears a note in Middle English on f. [45a] verso about a plant the author calls 'botrachium or batrachium', which probably refers to the plant now known as water crowfoot or (Ranunculus subgenus Batrachium). A section of text about the medicinal properties of the plant 'Botracion' begins on f. 45v at the red decorative initial 'B', and so it seems that this note was added to preserve further information about the plant. The slip is written in the same hand that added. f. [60a] to the volume and is on similar paper.

Post-medieval paper slip, f. [60a] fixed in the gutter between ff. 60v and 61r. The slip bears a note in Middle English on f. [60a] verso about a medical ingredient 'cinnabaris a stone called a sanguinari it is called dragons blood'; the author is almost certainly referring to the mineral cinnabar (mercury(II) sulfide (HgS)). A section of text about the medicinal properties of cinnabar begins on f. 61r at the green decorative initial 'C', and so it seems that the note was added to preserve further information about this mineral. The slip is written in the same hand that added. f. [45a] to the volume and is on similar paper.
